&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;16.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Concentrations of Credit Risk&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Company maintains amounts on account with financial institutions, which at times may exceed federally insured limits. The Company has not experienced any losses on such accounts.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Our primary concentration of credit risk is related to certain trade accounts receivable.&amp;nbsp; In the normal course of business, we extend unsecured credit to our customers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We investigate a customer&amp;#x2019;s credit worthiness before extending credit.&amp;nbsp; At December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015, three customers accounted for 28% of accounts receivable.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Principles of Consolidation&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Inventure Foods and all of its wholly owned subsidiaries.&amp;nbsp; All significant intercompany amounts and transactions have been eliminated.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Our fiscal year ends on the last Saturday occurring in the month of December&amp;nbsp;of each calendar year.&amp;nbsp; Accordingly, the fiscal year end dates result in an additional week of results every five or six years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Fiscal 2016 commenced December 27, 2015 and ended December 31, 2016, resulting in a 53-week fiscal year.&amp;nbsp; Fiscal 2015 commenced December 28, 2014 and ended December 26, 2015, resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Fiscal 2014 commenced December 29, 2013 and ended December 27, 2014, resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;8.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Term Debt and Line of Credit&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;ABL Credit Facility&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On November 18, 2015, the Company entered into a five-year revolving credit agreement with Wells Fargo Bank, National Association (&amp;#x201C;Wells Fargo&amp;#x201D;), as administrative agent, and the other lenders party thereto (with all related loan documents, and as amended from time to time, the &amp;#x201C;ABL Credit Facility&amp;#x201D;), replacing our Prior Credit Facility.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;All commitments under the Prior Credit Facility were terminated and all outstanding borrowings thereunder were repaid effective November 18, 2015.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The remaining obligations of the Company and its subsidiaries under the Prior Credit Facility generally are limited to certain remaining contingent indemnification obligations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The ABL Credit Facility provides for a five-year, $50.0 million senior secured revolving credit facility.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The ABL Credit Facility also provides that, under certain conditions, we may increase the aggregate principal amount of loans outstanding thereunder by up to $10.0 million.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;On November 18, 2015, we borrowed $21.9 million under the ABL Credit Facility.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We used the initial borrowing under that facility, together with the proceeds from the Term Loan Credit Facility (described below) to repay all outstanding borrowings under the Prior Credit Facility (consisting of $101.1 million), to pay accrued interest with respect to such loans, and to fund the payment of certain fees and costs relating to the Credit Facilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The ABL Credit Facility will mature, and the commitments thereunder will terminate, on November 17, 2020. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Company and all of its subsidiaries are borrowers under the ABL Credit Facility.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Subject to certain exceptions, the obligations under the ABL Credit Facility are secured by a lien on substantially all of the assets of the Company including: (i) a perfected first priority pledge of all the equity interests of the Company, and (ii) a perfected first priority security interest in substantially all other tangible and intangible assets of the Company and its subsidiaries (including, but not limited, to accounts receivable, inventory, equipment, general intangibles, investment property, real property, intellectual property and the proceeds of the foregoing).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The obligations under the ABL Credit Facility are also guaranteed by each of the Company&amp;#x2019;s subsidiaries.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Availability of borrowings under the ABL Credit Facility is subject to, among other things, a borrowing base calculation based upon a valuation of our eligible accounts and eligible inventory (including eligible finished goods, raw materials, and by-products inventory), each multiplied by an applicable advance rate or limit, and certain reserves and caps customary for financings of this type.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If at any time the aggregate amounts outstanding under the ABL Credit Facility exceed the borrowing base then in effect, a prepayment of an amount sufficient to eliminate such excess is required to be made.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Availability of borrowings under the ABL Credit Facility is also subject to a bring down of the representations and warranties in such Facility and the absence of any default thereunder (including any such default under our financial and other covenants in our Term Loan Credit Facility described below).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Voluntary prepayments of revolving loans under the ABL Credit Facility are permitted at any time, in whole or in part, without premium or penalty.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Borrowings under the ABL Credit Facility bear interest, at the Company&amp;#x2019;s option, at a base rate or LIBOR plus, in each case, an applicable margin.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;LIBOR is reset at the beginning of each selected interest period based on the LIBOR rate then in effect; provided that, if LIBOR is below zero, then such rate will be equal to zero plus the applicable margin.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The base rate is a fluctuating interest rate equal to the highest of (i) the federal funds effective rate from time to time plus 0.50%, (ii) LIBOR (after taking account of any applicable floor) applicable for an interest period of one month plus 1.00%, and (iii) the prime lending rate announced from time to time by Wells Fargo.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The applicable margin is subject to adjustment based on the Company&amp;#x2019;s Average Excess Availability (as defined in the ABL Credit Facility).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Additionally, to maintain availability of funds under the ABL Credit Facility, we pay a monthly commitment fee of 0.25&amp;#x2013;0.375% per annum, depending on the average ABL Credit Facility balance, on the unused portion of the ABL Credit Facility.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Ongoing extensions of credit under the ABL Credit Facility are subject to customary conditions, including sufficient availability under the borrowing base.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The ABL Credit Facility also contains covenants that require the Company to, among other things, periodically furnish financial and other information to the various lenders.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The ABL Credit Facility contains customary negative covenant and also requires the Company, together with its subsidiaries, to comply with a Fixed Charge Coverage Ratio (as defined in the ABL Credit Facility) upon exceeding certain minimum availability requirements. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Events of default under the ABL Credit Facility include customary events such as a cross-default provision with respect to other material debt. As of December 31, 2016, the Company is in compliance with all covenants of the ABL Credit Facility, except for the requirement to deliver audited financial statements without a going concern opinion.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We have obtained a temporary waiver of the going concern qualification until May 15, 2017 from the lenders under the ABL Credit Facility. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We use the ABL Credit Facility, in part, to fund our seasonal working capital needs, which are affected by, among other things, the growing cycles of the fruits and vegetables we process, for capital expenditures and for other general corporate purposes. The vast majority of our fruit and vegetable inventories are produced during the harvesting and packing months of June through September and depleted through the remaining eight months. Accordingly, our need to draw funds under the ABL Credit Facility fluctuates significantly during the year. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;As of December 31, 2016, there was $32.8 million outstanding under the ABL Credit Facility and the net availability thereunder was $10.3 million. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Term debt consisted of the following as of December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015 (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

						&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:08.08%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size:10pt;padding-right:3.6pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;84,150
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.00%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.54%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;

serif;font-size:10pt;padding-right:3.6pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;89,383
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:00.52%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Term Loan Credit Facility&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Also on November 18, 2015 and concurrent with the execution of the ABL Credit Facility, Inventure Foods and certain of its subsidiaries entered into a five-year term loan credit agreement (the &amp;#x201C;Term Loan Credit Facility&amp;#x201D;), with BSP Agency, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (&amp;#x201C;BSP&amp;#x201D;), as administrative agent, and the other lenders party thereto.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Term Loan Credit Facility provides for a $85.0 million senior secured term loan that matures on November 17, 2020.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Term Loan Credit Facility also provides that, under certain conditions, we may increase the aggregate principal amount of term loans outstanding thereunder by up to $25.0 million.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As noted above, we used the proceeds of the Term Loan Credit Facility, together with certain proceeds of the ABL Credit Facility, to refinance the indebtedness under the Prior Credit Facility and to fund payment of certain fees and costs related to the Credit Facilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Unlike amounts repaid under the ABL Credit Facility, any amounts we repay under the Term Loan Credit Facility may not be reborrowed.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Term Loan Credit Facility also matures on November 17, 2020. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Company and all of its subsidiaries are borrowers under the Term Loan Credit Facility.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Subject to certain exceptions, the obligations under the Term Loan Credit Facility are secured by substantially all of the assets of the Company including: (i) a perfected first priority pledge of all the equity interests of the Company, and (ii) a perfected first priority security interest in substantially all other tangible and intangible assets of the Company (including, but not limited, to accounts receivable, inventory, equipment, general intangibles, investment property, real property, intellectual property and the proceeds of the foregoing). &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Borrowings under the Term Loan Credit Facility bear interest, at the Company&amp;#x2019;s option, at a base rate or LIBOR plus, in each case, an applicable margin.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;LIBOR is reset at the beginning of each selected interest period based on the LIBOR rate then in effect; provided that, if LIBOR is below zero, then such rate will be equal to zero plus the applicable margin.&amp;nbsp; The base rate is a fluctuating interest rate equal to the highest of (i) the federal funds effective rate from time to time plus 0.50%, (ii) LIBOR (after taking account of any applicable floor) applicable for an interest period of one month plus 1.00%, and (iii) the prime lending rate announced by Wells Fargo.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The applicable margin is subject to adjustment based on the Company&amp;#x2019;s Total Leverage Ratio (as defined in the Term Loan Credit Facility). &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Term Loan Credit Facility requires amortization in the form of quarterly scheduled principal payments of $212,500 per fiscal quarter from March 2016 to September 2020, with the remaining balance due on the maturity date of November 17, 2020.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In addition to the scheduled quarterly principal payments, the Company is required to make mandatory principal payments out of Excess Cash Flow (as defined in the Term Loan Credit Facility)&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Term Loan Credit Facility also contains affirmative and negative covenants that require the Company to, among other things, periodically furnish financial and other information to the various lenders.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Term Loan Credit Facility contains customary negative covenants and also requires the Company, together with its subsidiaries, to comply with a Fixed Charge Coverage Ratio (as defined in the Term Loan Credit Facility) and a Total Leverage Ratio (as defined in the Term Loan Credit Facility).&amp;nbsp; On September 27, 2016, the Company entered into that certain Second Amendment to Credit Agreement with BSP, as the administrative agent, and the other lenders party thereto (the &amp;#x201C;Second Amendment&amp;#x201D;). The Second Amendment defers compliance with the Company&amp;#x2019;s Total Leverage Ratio and Fixed Charge Coverage Ratio covenants until the second quarter of fiscal 2017, requires the Company to comply with a minimum EBITDA covenant commencing with the fiscal month ending April 30, 2017, and increases the Base Rate Margin and the Libor Rate Margin thereunder by 100 basis points.&amp;nbsp; The Second Amendment also amends the fees payable to the lenders in the event of prepayment and restricts the Company&amp;#x2019;s ability to raise Curative Equity (as defined in the Second Amendment) until the fourth quarter of fiscal 2017.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Events of default under the Term Loan Credit Agreement include customary events such as a cross-default provision with respect to other material debt.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December 31, 2016 the Company is in compliance with all covenants of the Term Loan Credit Agreement, except for the requirement to deliver audited financial statements without a going concern opinion.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We have obtained a temporary waiver of the going concern qualification until May 15, 2017 from the lenders under the Term Loan Credit Facility. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;As of December 31, 2016, the amount outstanding under the Term Loan Credit Facility was $84.0 million and the interest rate payable was 9.0%.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Voluntary prepayments of amounts outstanding under the term loan are subject to a 2% prepayment penalty.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Equipment Loans&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In August 2015, we entered into an equipment term loan with Banc of America Leasing &amp;amp; Capital LLC for $3.1 million to finance new kettles and related equipment for our Goodyear, Arizona facility.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The equipment term loan accrues interest at a rate of 3.07% and will be repaid over 60 recurring monthly payments commencing May 2016.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In August 2014, we entered into two separate equipment term loans with Banc of America Leasing &amp;amp; Capital LLC; one for $2.6 million to finance equipment to be used at the Company&amp;#x2019;s Rader Farms facility, and the other for $1.9 million to finance equipment to be used at Willamette Valley Fruit Company.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Both of these equipment term loans accrue interest at a rate of 2.35% and will be repaid over 60 recurring monthly payments commencing September 15, 2014.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Debt Classification&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In accordance with FASB Accounting Standard Codification (&amp;#x201C;ASC&amp;#x201D;) 470-10-45 on Debt Presentation, all of the Company&amp;#x2019;s outstanding debt has been reclassified in the accompanying condensed consolidated balance sheet as a current liability as of December 31, 2016.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Absent the Second Amendment, the Company would not have been in compliance with the Total Leverage Ratio covenant as of December 31, 2016.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Unless we engage in a strategic transaction that enables us to pay down or refinance our debt,&amp;nbsp;or we secure a waiver from our lenders&amp;nbsp;or a further loan amendment to the Term Loan Credit Facility, we&amp;nbsp;will&amp;nbsp;not be in compliance with our financial covenants&amp;nbsp;at the end of the second quarter of fiscal 2017.&amp;nbsp; As previously announced, the Company commenced a comprehensive strategic and financial review of the Company&amp;#x2019;s operations and engaged Rothschild Inc. to serve as its financial advisor to assist the Company in this process, including the pursuit of value-enhancing initiatives including, a sale of the Company, a sale of assets of the Company or other strategic business combination, or other capital structure optimization opportunities.&amp;nbsp;This comprehensive strategic and financial review remains ongoing as of the date of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;There can be no assurances that these efforts will result in a completion of a transaction or, if one is completed, that it will be on favorable terms.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;A default under the Term Loan Credit Facility would trigger a default under the ABL Credit Facility and certain of our equipment lease financing arrangements, as these facilities each contain cross-default provisions. As such, we reclassified all of our outstanding debt as a current liability.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Derivative Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We have utilized interest rate swaps in the management of our variable interest rate exposure and do not enter into derivatives for trading purposes.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;All derivatives are measured at fair value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our interest rate swaps are classified as cash flow hedges. In fiscal 2015, the Company settled all existing interest rate swaps as part of our debt refinancing.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015 the Company did not have any interest rate swaps.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Earnings (Loss) Per Common Share&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Basic earnings (loss) per common share is computed by dividing net income (loss) by the weighted average number of shares of Common Stock outstanding during the period.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Diluted earnings (loss) per share is calculated by including all dilutive common shares such as stock options and restricted stock.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For the fiscal years ended December 31, 2016, December 26, 2015 and December 27, 2014, there were 0.5 million, &amp;nbsp;0.6 million and 0.1 million shares of Common Stock, respectively, underlying stock options and restricted stock units that were not included in the computation of diluted earnings (loss) per share because inclusion of such shares would be antidilutive or because the exercise prices were greater than the average market price of Common Stock for the applicable period.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Exercises of outstanding stock options or warrants are assumed to occur for purposes of calculating diluted earnings (loss) per share for periods in which their effect would not be anti-dilutive.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Earnings (loss) per common share was computed as follows for the fiscal years ended December 31, 2016, December 26, 2015 and December 27, 2014 (in thousands, except per share data):&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

						&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:07.38%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;;font-family:Times New Roman

				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.14%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;padding:0pt;&gt;

		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Fair Value of Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability (i.e., the &amp;#x201C;exit price&amp;#x201D;) in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We classify our investments based upon an established fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (Level 1 measurement) and the lowest priority to unobservable inputs (Level 3 measurement).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The three levels of the fair value hierarchy are described as follows:&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77.05pt;text-indent: -41.05pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;Level 1&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Unadjusted quoted prices in active markets that are accessible at the measurement date for identical, unrestricted assets or liabilities.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77.05pt;text-indent: -41.05pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;Level 2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Quoted prices in markets that are not considered to be active or financial instruments without quoted market prices, but for which all significant inputs are observable, either directly or indirectly.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77.05pt;text-indent: -41.05pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;Level 3&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Prices or valuations that require inputs that are both significant to the fair value measurement and unobservable.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;A financial instrument&amp;#x2019;s level within the fair value hierarchy is based on the lowest level of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;At December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015, the carrying value of cash, accounts receivable, accounts payable and accrued liabilities approximate fair values since they are short term in nature.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The carrying value of the long-term debt approximates fair value based on the borrowing rates currently available to us for long-term borrowings with similar terms.&amp;nbsp; The following table summarizes the valuation of our assets and liabilities measured at fair value on a recurring basis (in thousands) at the respective dates set forth below:&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%;&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 align=center style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.04%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;overflow: hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.64%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;overflow: hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:06.24%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Considerable judgment is required in interpreting market data to develop the estimate of fair value of our assets and liabilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accordingly, the estimate may not be indicative of the amounts that we could realize in a current market exchange.&amp;nbsp; The use of different market assumptions or valuation methodologies could have a material effect on the estimated fair value amounts.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Company&amp;#x2019;s non-qualified deferred compensation plan assets consist of money market and mutual funds invested in domestic and international marketable securities that are directly observable in active markets. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The fair value measurement of the earn-out contingent consideration obligation relates to the acquisitions of Sin In A Tin &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:5pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt; in September 2014 and Willamette Valley Fruit Company in May 2013, and is included in accrued liabilities and other long-term liabilities in the consolidated balance sheets.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The fair value measurement is based upon significant inputs not observable in the market.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Changes in the value of the obligation are recorded as income or expense in our consolidated statements of operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;To determine the fair value, we valued the contingent consideration liability based on the expected probability weighted earn-out payments corresponding to the performance thresholds agreed to under the applicable purchase agreements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The expected earn-out payments were then present valued by applying a discount rate that captures a market participants view of the risk associated with the expected earn-out payments. In fiscal 2016 and 2015, we increased our estimate of the total earn-out expected to be achieved, which resulted in an increase in operating expenses of $0.3 million and&amp;nbsp; $0.3 million during the years ended December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015, respectively.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;A summary of the activity of the fair value of the measurements using unobservable inputs (Level 3 Liabilities) for the year ended December 31, 2016, is as follows (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman

serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;

			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The trademarks, except for the Fresh Frozen Foods trademark, are deemed to have an indefinite useful life because they are expected to generate cash flows indefinitely.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;At December 31, 2016, in connection with the annual impairment test of the Fresh Frozen Foods trademark, it was determined that this trademark has a definite live of ten years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Therefore starting on January 1, 2017 the Fresh Frozen Foods trademark will be amortized over a ten year term.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Amortization expense was $0.3 million, $0.5 million and $1.2 million for the fiscal years ended December 31, 2016, December 26, 2015 and December 27, 2014, respectively.&amp;nbsp; As of December 31, 2016, we expect amortization expense on these intangible assets over the next five years to be as follows (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;

				&lt;/td&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

						&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;$&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:10.02%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size:10pt;padding-right:3.6pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;2,084
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:01.22%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Goodwill and trademarks are reviewed for impairment annually in the fourth fiscal quarter, or more frequently if impairment indicators arise.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Goodwill is required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change that more-likely-than-not reduces the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Intangible assets with indefinite lives are required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change indicating that the asset might be impaired.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Intangible Assets&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Goodwill and trademarks are reviewed for impairment annually or more frequently if impairment indicators arise.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Goodwill, by reporting unit, is required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change that more-likely-than-not reduces the fair value of a reporting unit below its carrying value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We have concluded from our annual impairment testing performed in December&amp;nbsp;there was impairment of the goodwill created in the acquisition of Fresh Frozen Foods in 2013. Due to declining sales from our Fresh Frozen business since the product recall the fair value of the reporting unit was determined to be below the carrying value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We performed the step 2 impairment test which resulted in no implied fair value of goodwill, and therefore we recognized a recognized an impairment charge of $8.3 million.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Intangible assets with indefinite lives are required to be tested for impairment between the annual tests if an event occurs or circumstances change indicating that the asset might be impaired.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In fiscal 2016, the Company The fair value of the Fresh Frozen trademark was determined to be 2.3 million based on a discounted cash flow approach, and therefore we recognized and impairment charge of $7.1 million.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In 2015, as a result of the product recall (see Note 2 &amp;#x201C;Product Recall&amp;#x201D;) we concluded that the intangible asset related to the acquired customer relationships of Fresh Frozen Foods was fully impaired.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accordingly, the Company recorded an intangible asset impairment charge of $9.3 million.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Management believes that each of our trademarks has the continued ability to generate cash flows indefinitely.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Therefore, each of our trademarks has been determined to have an indefinite life.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Management&amp;#x2019;s determination that our trademarks have indefinite lives includes an evaluation of historical cash flows and projected cash flows for each of these trademarks.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In addition, there are no legal, regulatory, contractual, economic or other factors to limit the useful life of these trademarks.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Management intends to renew each of these trademarks, which can be accomplished at little cost.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Amortizable intangible assets are amortized using the straight-line method over their estimated useful lives, which is the estimated period over which economic benefits are expected to be provided.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;See Note 4 &amp;#x201C;Goodwill, Trademarks and Other Intangible Assets&amp;#x201D; for additional information.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;11.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Income Taxes&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 11pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In fiscal 2016 a valuation allowance of $12.6 million was recorded against our net deferred tax asset &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:11pt;&gt;upon determining it is more likely than not that the deferred tax assets will not be realized&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;. In addition, the net deferred tax liability related to goodwill and other indefinite-lived assets was not used as a future source of income in the valuation allowance analysis. Accordingly, this deferred tax liability is recorded on our balance sheet.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;

				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.16%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

		&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Income Taxes&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We account for income taxes under the asset and liability method, which requires the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Under this method, deferred tax assets and liabilities are determined based on the differences between the financial statements and tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The effect of a change in tax rates on deferred tax assets and liabilities is recognized in income in the period that includes the enactment date.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We record net deferred tax assets to the extent we believe these assets will more likely than not be realized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;A valuation allowance is provided when it is more likely than not that some portion or all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In making such determination, we consider all available positive and negative evidence, including future reversals of existing taxable temporary differences, projected future taxable income, tax planning strategies and recent financial operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;A significant piece of objective negative evidence evaluated was the cumulative losses incurred in recent years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Such objective evidence limits the ability to consider other subjective evidence such as our projections for future taxable income.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In light of our continued losses, at December&amp;nbsp;31, 2016, we determined that our deferred tax liabilities were not sufficient to fully realize our deferred tax assets and, as a result, a valuation allowance of $12.6 million was recorded against our net deferred tax asset. In addition, the net deferred tax liability related to goodwill and other indefinite-lived assets was not used as a future source of income in the valuation allowance analysis. Accordingly, this deferred tax liability is recorded on our balance sheet.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Company uses a two-step approach to recognize and measure uncertain tax positions.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The first step is to evaluate the tax position for recognition by determining if the weight of available evidence indicates that it is more likely than not that the position will be sustained on audit, including resolutions of related appeals or litigation processes, if any.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The second step is to measure the tax benefit as the largest amount that is more likely than not of being realized upon ultimate settlement.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company believes that its income tax filing positions and deductions would be sustained upon examination; thus, the Company has not recorded any uncertain tax positions as of December 31, 2016.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;It is our policy to recognize interest and penalties accrued on any unrecognized tax benefits as a component of income tax expense.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We do not have any accrued interest or penalties associated with unrecognized tax benefits for the fiscal years 2016 and 2015. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We file income tax returns in the U.S. federal jurisdiction and various state jurisdictions.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The material jurisdictions that are subject to examination by tax authorities include the U.S. federal, Arizona, California, Georgia, Indiana and Oregon.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our U.S. federal income tax returns for fiscal 2013 through 2015 remain open to examination by the Internal Revenue Service.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our state tax returns for fiscal 2012 through 2015 remain open to examination by the state jurisdictions.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;6.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Inventories&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Inventories consisted of the following as of December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015 (in thousands):&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%;&gt;&lt;table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 align=center style=border-collapse:collapse;width: 80.00%;margin-left:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:71.34%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;overflow: hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.06%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;overflow: hidden;font-size:0pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
