		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Inventories&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Inventories are stated at the lower of cost (first-in, first-out) or market.&amp;nbsp; We identify slow moving or obsolete inventories and estimate appropriate write-down provisions related thereto.&amp;nbsp; If actual market conditions are less favorable than those projected by management, additional inventory write downs may be required.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In the ordinary course of business, we manage price and supply risk of commodities by entering into various short-term purchase arrangements with our vendors.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;13.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Legal Proceedings&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We are periodically a party to various lawsuits arising in the ordinary course of business.&amp;nbsp; Management believes, based on discussions with legal counsel, that the resolution of any such lawsuits, individually and in the aggregate,&amp;nbsp;will not have a material adverse effect on our financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-style:italic;&gt;Indemnification Request&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On or about February 17, 2016, the Company received a letter from one of its commercial customers requesting indemnity with respect to a lawsuit threatened against the customer in Florida alleging that certain kettle chip products sold by the customer and manufactured by the Company were improperly labeled as &amp;#x201C;natural.&amp;#x201D;&amp;nbsp; On March 7, 2016, the Company informed the commercial customer that the Company had no obligation to indemnify the commercial customer with respect to the matter.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-style:italic;&gt;Litigation&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On April 4, 2016, a purported class action captioned Westmoreland County Employee Retirement Fund (&amp;#x201C;Westmoreland&amp;#x201D;) v. Inventure Foods Inc. et al., Case No. CV2016-002718, was filed in the Superior Court in Maricopa County, Arizona. Additional defendants are the Company&amp;#x2019;s Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer, and the underwriters of the secondary securities offering that closed September 14, 2014 (the &amp;#x201C;September 2014 Offering&amp;#x201D;).&amp;nbsp; The class action complaint, which was amended a second time on March 27, 2017, alleges violations of Sections 11, 12(a)(2) and 15 of the Securities Act and focuses on the conditions at the Company&amp;#x2019;s former frozen food facility in Jefferson, Georgia.&amp;nbsp; Westmoreland seeks certification as a class action, unspecified compensatory damages, rescission or a rescissory measure of damages, attorneys&amp;#x2019; fees and costs, and other relief deemed appropriate by the court.&amp;nbsp; The Company, its Chief Executive Officer, its Chief Financial Officer and the September 2014 Offering underwriters have not yet responded to the second amended complaint. The Company is vigorously defending against the claims.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On November 10, 2016, the Center for Environment Health (&amp;#x201C;CEH&amp;#x201D;), represented by Howard Hirsch of Lexington Law Group, filed a lawsuit against Company under the California Safe Drinking Water and Toxic Enforcement Act (known as &amp;#x201C;Proposition 65&amp;#x201D;) (the &amp;#x201C;Act&amp;#x201D;).&amp;nbsp; CEH contends that the Company&amp;#x2019;s potato-based chip products contain amounts of acrylamide in excess of what is permitted under the Act.&amp;nbsp; An Inventure retailer, Bristol Farms, demanded indemnity in relation to the litigation.&amp;nbsp; The Company has answered the complaint and intends to vigorously defend the lawsuit. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On November 14, 2016, Michelle Blair (represented by Matthew Armstrong of Armstrong Law Firm LLC and Stuart Cochran of Cochran Law PLLC) filed a putative class action against the Company in St. Louis City Circuit Court.&amp;nbsp; Ms. Blair purports to represent a class of consumers who purchased one of nine Boulder Canyon brand products listing &amp;#x201C;evaporated cane juice&amp;#x201D; as an ingredient.&amp;nbsp; Ms. Blair contends that the use of &amp;#x201C;evaporated cane juice&amp;#x201D; was misleading because evaporated cane juice is sugar.&amp;nbsp; In the complaint, Ms. Blair advances claims for violation of Missouri&amp;#x2019;s Merchandising Practices Act, Mo. Rev. Stat. &amp;#xA7; 407.020, et seq. and 15 C.S.R. 60-8.020, et seq., and unjust enrichment.&amp;nbsp; On February 3, 2017, the Company removed the action to the Eastern District of Missouri. Plaintiff dismissed the removed action without prejudice and refiled a substantially similar complaint in the Southern District of Illinois. The new complaint is brought by Ms. Blair and a new plaintiff, Shannah Burton, and asserts a nationwide putative class.&amp;nbsp; The Company intends to vigorously defend the lawsuit.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On March 9, 2017, a verified stockholder derivative complaint was filed under seal in the U.S. District Court for the District of Arizona, Case No. 2:17-cv-00727, against certain of its current and former officers and directors&amp;#x2014;Terry&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;McDaniel, Steve Weinberger, Timothy A. Cole, Ashton D. Asensio, Macon Bryce Edmonson, Paul J. Lapadat, Harold S. Edwards, David I. Meyers, and Itzhak Reichman.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The lawsuit also names the Company as a nominal defendant.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The under seal complaint focuses on the conditions at the Company&amp;#x2019;s former frozen food facility in Jefferson, Georgia and the Company&amp;#x2019;s 2015 and 2016 proxy statements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The plaintiff&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;purports to derivatively assert on behalf of the Company claims for alleged violation of Section 14(a) of the Exchange Act, breach of fiduciary duty, waste of corporate assets and unjust enrichment.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;According to the complaint, the plaintiff seeks an unspecified award of actual or compensatory damages in favor of the Company; an order directing the Company to take certain actions concerning its corporate governance and internal procedures, including putting forward certain proposals concerning its corporate governance policies and amendments to the Company&amp;#x2019;s Bylaws and Articles of Incorporation for a stockholder vote; an award of extraordinary equitable and/or injunctive relief concerning the defendants&amp;#x2019; trading activities or their assets; restitution from defendants to Inventure consisting of a disgorgement of all profits, benefits and other compensation obtained by defendants; costs and disbursements of the action, including attorneys, accountant and experts&amp;#x2019; fees, costs and expenses; and other and further relief as the court deems just and proper. The Company intends to vigorously defend the lawsuit.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On March 27, 2017, a purported class action captioned Glenn Schoenfeld v. Inventure Foods, Inc., et al.,Case No. 2:17-cv-00910, was filed in the U.S. District Court for the District of Arizona purportedly on behalf of all persons and entities that acquired Inventure securities between March 3, 2016 and March 16, 2017.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company&amp;#x2019;s Chief Executive Officer and Chief Financial Officer are also named as defendants.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The complaint, which focuses on the conditions of the Company&amp;#x2019;s former frozen food facility in Jefferson, Georgia, asserts claims for alleged violation of Sections 10(b) and 20(a) of the Exchange Act in connection with the Company&amp;#x2019;s press releases and SEC filings between March 3, 2016 and March 16, 2017.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Mr. Schoenfeld seeks certification as a class action, unspecified compensatory damages, attorneys&amp;#x2019; fees, costs and expenses incurred in the action, and other relief deemed appropriate by the court.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company intends to vigorously defend the lawsuit.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-style:italic;&gt;Pre-Lawsuit Notifications and Demands&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On July 11, 2016, the Company received a pre-lawsuit notification and demand from Farbod Nikravesh (represented by Barbara Rohr of Faruqi &amp;amp; Faruqi), who purported to represent a class of purchasers of Boulder Canyon brand products advertised as &amp;#x201C;All Natural.&amp;#x201D;&amp;nbsp; The Company removed the challenged language (&amp;#x201C;All Natural&amp;#x201D;) from its packaging before receiving the letter.&amp;nbsp; Mr. Farbod expressed intent to file a class action under California&amp;#x2019;s consumer protection statutes.&amp;nbsp; The parties resolved the matter on a confidential basis with no lawsuit being filed. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On July 11, 2016, the Company received a pre-lawsuit notification and demand from Maryanne McGuiness and Christine Sellers (represented by Tim Howard of Howard &amp;amp; Associates), who purported to represent a class of purchasers of Boulder Canyon kettle chips advertised as &amp;#x201C;All Natural&amp;#x201D; and &amp;#x201C;Non-GMO.&amp;#x201D;&amp;nbsp; The Company removed the &amp;#x201C;All Natural&amp;#x201D; language from its packaging before receiving the letter.&amp;nbsp; The claimants expressed intent to file a class action under Florida&amp;#x2019;s consumer protection statutes.&amp;nbsp; The parties resolved the matter on a confidential basis with no lawsuit being filed. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Recent Accounting Pronouncements &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Changes to GAAP are established by the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&amp;#x201C;FASB&amp;#x201D;) in the form of accounting standards updates (&amp;#x201C;ASU&amp;#x201D;) to the FASB&amp;#x2019;s Accounting Standards Codification.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We consider the applicability and impact of all ASUs.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;ASUs not listed below were assessed and determined to be either not applicable or are expected to have minimal impact on our consolidated financial position or results of operations.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In May 2014, the FASB issued new guidance related to revenue recognition.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This new standard will replace all current GAAP guidance on this topic and eliminate all industry-specific guidance.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The new revenue recognition standard provides a unified model to determine when and how revenue is recognized.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The core principle is that a company should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration for which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This guidance will be effective at the beginning of our 2018 fiscal year and can be applied either retrospectively to each period presented or as a cumulative-effect adjustment as of the date of adoption.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December 31, 2016, we have not evaluated the impact of this new accounting standard on our financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In August 2014, FASB issued an ASU requiring an entity to perform a going concern assessment by evaluating its ability to meet its obligations for a look-forward period of one year from the financial statement issuance date. Disclosures are required if it is probable an entity will be unable to meet its obligations within the look-forward period. Incremental substantial doubt disclosure is required if the probability is not mitigated by management&amp;#x2019;s plans. The guidance is effective for all entities for the first annual period ending after December&amp;nbsp;15, 2016 and interim periods thereafter. Early application is permitted. We adopted this ASU for the year ended December 31, 2016 and the Company&amp;#x2019;s evaluation determined that there is substantial doubt about our ability to continue as a going concern.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As such, disclosures have been made in accordance with this ASU. &amp;nbsp;As the guidance only impacts disclosure, the adoption of this guidance did not have any impact on our financial condition, results of operations and cash flows.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In April 2015, the FASB issued an ASU to simplify the presentation of debt issuance costs. This ASU requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, consistent with debt discounts. The recognition and measurement guidance for debt issuance costs are not affected by this ASU. This ASU is effective for fiscal years, and interim periods within those years, beginning after December 15, 2015, and is applied retrospectively. We adopted this ASU in the first quarter of fiscal 2016.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The adoption of this ASU reduced our other assets and long-term debt, less current portion, by $7.0 million and $5.4 million as of December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015, respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In July 2015, the FASB issued an ASU to simplify the measurement of inventory.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This ASU requires inventory to be subsequently measured using the lower of cost and net realizable value, thereby eliminating the market value approach. Net realizable value is defined as the &amp;#x201C;estimated selling prices in the ordinary course of business, less reasonably predictable costs of completion, disposal and transportation.&amp;#x201D;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This ASU is effective for reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2016 and is applied prospectively. Early adoption is permitted. We will adopt this ASU in the first quarter of fiscal 2017 and do not anticipate the adoption to have a material impact on our financial statements and disclosure.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In November 2015, the FASB issued an ASU that simplifies the presentation of deferred taxes by requiring deferred tax assets and liabilities to be offset and presented as a single noncurrent amount on the balance sheet. This ASU is effective for reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2016 and can be applied either retrospectively or prospectively. We adopted this ASU in the third quarter of fiscal 2016 on a retrospective basis.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Therefore, our December 26, 2015 deferred tax asset of $3.8 million and deferred tax liability of&amp;nbsp;$2.6 million are now presented as a single noncurrent deferred tax asset of $1.2 million.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In February 2016, the FASB issued new guidance related to accounting for leases. The new standard requires the recognition of assets and liabilities arising from lease transactions on the balance sheet and the disclosure of key information about leasing arrangements. Accordingly, a lessee will recognize a lease asset for its right to use the underlying asset and a lease liability for the corresponding lease obligation. Both the asset and liability will initially be measured at the present value of the future minimum lease payments over the lease term. Subsequent measurement, including the presentation of expenses and cash flows, will depend on the classification of the lease as either a finance or an operating lease. The new standard is effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2018, and interim periods within those years. Early adoption is permitted.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As of December 31, 2016, we have not evaluated the impact of this new accounting standard on our financial statements.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In March 2016, the FASB issued an ASU intended to simplify various aspects of the accounting for share-based payments. Excess tax benefits for share-based payments will be recorded as a reduction of income taxes and reflected in operating cash flows upon the adoption of this ASU. Excess tax benefits are currently recorded in equity and as financing activity under the current rules. This guidance is effective for reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2016. We will adopt this ASU in the first quarter of fiscal 2017 and do not anticipate the adoption to have a material impact on our financial statements and disclosure.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
&lt;div&gt; &lt;div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;1.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Operations and Summary of Significant Accounting Policies&lt;a name=a1OperationsandSummaryofSignificantAccou&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Description of Business&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Inventure Foods, Inc., a Delaware corporation (referred to herein as the &amp;#x201C;Company,&amp;#x201D; &amp;#x201C;Inventure Foods,&amp;#x201D; &amp;#x201C;we,&amp;#x201D; &amp;#x201C;our&amp;#x201D; or &amp;#x201C;us&amp;#x201D;), is a leading marketer and manufacturer of healthy/natural and indulgent specialty snack food brands with more than $269 million in annual net revenues for fiscal 2016.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We specialize in two primary product categories:&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;healthy/natural food products and indulgent specialty snack products.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We sell our products nationally through a number of channels including: grocery stores, natural food stores, mass merchandisers, drug and convenience stores, club stores, value, vending, food service, industrial and international.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our goal is to have a diversified portfolio of brands, products, customers and distribution channels. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In our healthy/natural food category, products include Rader Farms&amp;#xAE; frozen berries, Boulder Canyon&amp;#xAE; brand kettle cooked potato chips, other snack and food items, Willamette Valley Fruit Company&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:6.5pt;&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt; brand frozen berries, Fresh Frozen&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:6.5pt;&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt; brand frozen vegetables, fruits, biscuits and other frozen snacks, Jamba&amp;#xAE; brand blend-and-serve smoothie kits under license from Jamba Juice Company (&amp;#x201C;Jamba Juice&amp;#x201D;), Seattle&amp;#x2019;s Best Coffee&amp;#xAE; Frozen Coffee Blends brand blend-and-serve frozen coffee beverages under license from Seattle&amp;#x2019;s Best Coffee, LLC, Sin In A Tin&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:6.5pt;&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt; &amp;nbsp;chocolate pate and other frozen desserts and private label frozen fruit and healthy/natural snacks.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In our indulgent specialty snack food category, products include T.G.I. Friday&amp;#x2019;s&amp;#xAE; brand snacks under license from T.G.I. Friday&amp;#x2019;s Inc. (&amp;#x201C;T.G.I. Friday&amp;#x2019;s&amp;#x201D;), Nathan&amp;#x2019;s Famous&amp;#xAE; brand snack products under license from Nathan&amp;#x2019;s Famous Corporation, Vidalia&amp;#xAE; brand snack products under license from Vidalia Brands, Inc., Poore Brothers&amp;#xAE; brand kettle cooked potato chips, Bob&amp;#x2019;s Texas Style&amp;#xAE; brand kettle cooked chips, and Tato Skins&amp;#xAE; brand potato snacks.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We also manufacture private label snacks for certain grocery retail chains and co-pack products for other snack and cereal manufacturers.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We operate in two segments: frozen products and snack products.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The frozen products segment includes frozen fruits, vegetables, beverages and desserts for sale primarily to grocery stores, club stores and mass merchandisers. All products sold under our frozen products segment are considered part of the healthy/natural food category. The snack products segment includes potato chips, kettle chips, potato crisps, potato skins, pellet snacks, sheeted dough products, popcorn and extruded products for sale primarily to snack food distributors and retailers. The products sold under our snack products segment include products considered part of the indulgent specialty snack food category, as well as products considered part of the healthy/natural food category.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We operate manufacturing facilities in nine locations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our frozen berry products are processed in our Lynden, Washington, Bellingham, Washington, Jefferson, Georgia and two Salem, Oregon facilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our frozen berry business grows, processes and markets premium berry blends, raspberries, blueberries and rhubarb and purchases blackberries, cherries, cranberries, strawberries and other fruits from a select network of fruit growers for resale.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The fruit is processed, frozen and packaged for sale and distribution to wholesale customers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our frozen vegetable products are processed in our Jefferson, Georgia, Thomasville, Georgia and Salem, Oregon facilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our frozen beverage products are packaged at our Bellingham, Washington and Jefferson, Georgia facilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We also use third-party processors for certain frozen products and package certain frozen fruits and vegetables for other manufacturers.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our frozen desserts products are produced in our Pensacola, Florida and Salem, Oregon facilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our snack products are manufactured at our Phoenix, Arizona and Bluffton, Indiana facilities, as well as select third-party facilities for certain products.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On April 23, 2015, we announced a voluntary product recall of certain varieties of the Company&amp;#x2019;s Fresh Frozen&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:6.5pt;&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt; brand of frozen vegetables, as well as select varieties of our Jamba&amp;#xAE; &amp;#x201C;At Home&amp;#x201D; line of smoothie kits because our Jefferson, Georgia facility tested positive for Listeria monocytogenes.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;For a discussion of this product recall, refer to &amp;#x201C;Note 2 - Product Recall.&amp;#x201D;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Strategic and Financial Review Process&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;In July&amp;nbsp;2016, we announced that our Board had commenced a strategic and financial review of the Company with the objective to increase shareholder value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We engaged Rothschild Inc. to serve as our financial advisor and assist us in this process.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We remain actively involved in this process and are continuing to pursue various strategic alternatives.&amp;nbsp; As disclosed in our prior reports, no assurance can be given as to the outcome or timing of this process or that it will result in the consummation of any specific transaction.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Going Concern Uncertainty&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We have incurred losses from operations in each of the quarterly periods since our product recall in April 2015.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;This fact, together with the projected near term outlook for our business and our inability to complete a strategic transaction by year end or demonstrate that such a transaction is imminent, raise substantial doubt about our ability to continue as a going concern.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;In reaching such conclusion, management considered the following specific conditions:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table style=width:100%; cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=width:54pt;&gt;&lt;p style=width:54pt;font-size:0pt;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td valign=top align=left style=width: 17.00pt; display: inline;&gt;
			&lt;p style=font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;&gt;
				&lt;font style=margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;font-size:10pt;;&gt; &amp;#xB7;&lt;/font&gt;
			&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=width:1pt;&gt;&lt;p style=width:1pt;width:1pt;font-size:0pt;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td align=left valign=top&gt;
			&lt;p style=font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Our Term Loan Credit Facility and related governing documents contain requirements that, among other things, require us to comply with leverage ratio and fixed charge coverage ratio covenants by the end of the second quarter of fiscal 2017 and a minimum EBITDA target by the fiscal month ending April 30, 2017.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The leverage ratio, measured at the end of our second fiscal quarter in 2017 must be 4.25:1, and the fixed charge coverage ratio, measured at the end of our second fiscal quarter in 2017 for the four quarterly periods then ended, must be 4.25:1.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Absent the completion of a strategic transaction yielding sufficient cash proceeds (in addition to the proceeds received from the sale of our Fresh Frozen Foods assets in March 2017) to pay down debt, waivers or amendments by our lenders, or a refinancing of our debt we will not be able to comply with these covenants when required to do so.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Failure to meet these covenants would result in a default under such credit facility and, to the extent the applicable lenders so elect, an acceleration of the Company&amp;#x2019;s existing indebtedness, causing such debt of approximately $122.1 million at December 31, 2016 (including $5.2 million of other equipment financing indebtedness that includes cross-default provisions) to be immediately due and payable.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The Company does not have sufficient liquidity to repay all of its outstanding debt in full if such debt were accelerated.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table style=width:100%; cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=width:54pt;&gt;&lt;p style=width:54pt;font-size:0pt;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td valign=top align=left style=width: 17.00pt; display: inline;&gt;
			&lt;p style=font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;&gt;
				&lt;font style=margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;font-family:Symbol;font-size:10pt;;&gt; &amp;#xB7;&lt;/font&gt;
			&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=width:1pt;&gt;&lt;p style=width:1pt;width:1pt;font-size:0pt;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td align=left valign=top&gt;
			&lt;p style=font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Under our ABL Credit Facility, we are required to comply with a fixed charge coverage ratio if our liquidity as of the date of any determination is less than the greater of (i) 12.5% of the Maximum Revolver Amount&amp;nbsp; ($50,000,000) and (ii) $6,125,000, subject to certain conditions. As of the date of this Form 10-K, we would not be able to comply with this ratio if our liquidity were to fall below the applicable threshold. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;div style=width:100%&gt;&lt;table style=width:100%; cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=width:54pt;&gt;&lt;p style=width:54pt;font-size:0pt;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td valign=top align=left style=width: 17.00pt; display: inline;&gt;
			&lt;p style=font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;&gt;
				&lt;font style=margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;font-size:10pt;;&gt; &amp;#xB7;&lt;/font&gt;
			&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style=width:1pt;&gt;&lt;p style=width:1pt;width:1pt;font-size:0pt;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td align=left valign=top&gt;
			&lt;p style=font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Credit Facilities also require us to furnish our audited financial statements without a &amp;#x201C;going concern&amp;#x201D; uncertainty paragraph in the auditor&amp;#x2019;s opinion.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Our consolidated financial statements for the fiscal year ended December 31, 2016 included herein contain a &amp;#x201C;going concern&amp;#x201D; explanatory paragraph. Under the Credit Facilities, a going concern opinion with respect to our audited financial statements is an event of default.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;line-height:120%;text-indent:36pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Company&amp;#x2019;s Board and management are in the process of exploring various strategic alternatives.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We have obtained a temporary waiver of the going concern qualification until May 15, 2017 from each of the lenders under our Credit Facilities. There can be no assurance that we will be successful in our pursuit of any strategic transaction or that we will be able consummate a strategic transaction in time to address our financial covenant requirements and going concern qualification, or at all, or if we do complete a strategic transition it will be on commercially reasonable terms.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;As a result, our liquidity and ability to timely pay our obligations when due could be adversely affected.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The accompanying consolidated financial statements are prepared on a going concern basis and do not include any adjustments that might result from uncertainty about our ability to continue as a going concern, other than the reclassification of certain long-term debt and the related debt issuance costs to current liabilities and current assets, respectively.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Our lenders may resist renegotiation or lengthening of payment and other terms through legal action or otherwise if we are unsuccessful in our efforts to complete a strategic transaction.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;If we are not able to timely, successfully or efficiently implement the strategies that we are pursuing, we may need to voluntarily seek protection under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Acquisitions &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;We account for acquisitions using the acquisition method of accounting.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The results of operations of our acquired businesses have been included in our consolidated results from their respective dates of acquisition.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;On September 29, 2014, we acquired the assets and intellectual property of a small boutique frozen desserts business, Sin In A Tin &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:5pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;, for approximately $160,000 in cash. An additional amount of up to $0.5 million is payable to the seller in the form of an earn-out based on future net revenues attributable to Sin In A Tin &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:5pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt; products (see Note 3 &amp;#x201C;Acquisitions&amp;#x201D;).&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Principles of Consolidation&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of Inventure Foods and all of its wholly owned subsidiaries.&amp;nbsp; All significant intercompany amounts and transactions have been eliminated.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Our fiscal year ends on the last Saturday occurring in the month of December&amp;nbsp;of each calendar year.&amp;nbsp; Accordingly, the fiscal year end dates result in an additional week of results every five or six years.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Fiscal 2016 commenced December 27, 2015 and ended December 31, 2016, resulting in a 53-week fiscal year.&amp;nbsp; Fiscal 2015 commenced December 28, 2014 and ended December 26, 2015, resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Fiscal 2014 commenced December 29, 2013 and ended December 27, 2014, resulting in a 52-week fiscal year.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Use of Estimates&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&amp;#x201C;GAAP&amp;#x201D;) requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities, disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements, and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period.&amp;nbsp; We routinely evaluate our estimates, including those related to accruals for customer programs and incentives, product returns, bad debts, income taxes, long-lived assets, inventories, stock-based compensation, interest rate swap valuations, accrued broker commissions and contingencies.&amp;nbsp; We base our estimates on historical experience and on various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable under the circumstances.&amp;nbsp; Actual results could differ from those estimates.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;&gt;Fair Value of Financial Instruments&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Fair value is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability (i.e., the &amp;#x201C;exit price&amp;#x201D;) in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;We classify our investments based upon an established fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities (Level 1 measurement) and the lowest priority to unobservable inputs (Level 3 measurement).&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The three levels of the fair value hierarchy are described as follows:&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77.05pt;text-indent: -41.05pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;Level 1&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Unadjusted quoted prices in active markets that are accessible at the measurement date for identical, unrestricted assets or liabilities.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77.05pt;text-indent: -41.05pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;Level 2&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Quoted prices in markets that are not considered to be active or financial instruments without quoted market prices, but for which all significant inputs are observable, either directly or indirectly.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 77.05pt;text-indent: -41.05pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-weight:bold;&gt;Level 3&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Prices or valuations that require inputs that are both significant to the fair value measurement and unobservable.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;A financial instrument&amp;#x2019;s level within the fair value hierarchy is based on the lowest level of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;At December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015, the carrying value of cash, accounts receivable, accounts payable and accrued liabilities approximate fair values since they are short term in nature.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The carrying value of the long-term debt approximates fair value based on the borrowing rates currently available to us for long-term borrowings with similar terms.&amp;nbsp; The following table summarizes the valuation of our assets and liabilities measured at fair value on a recurring basis (in thousands) at the respective dates set forth below:&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman

serif;font-size: 1pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:1pt;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;

		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Considerable judgment is required in interpreting market data to develop the estimate of fair value of our assets and liabilities.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Accordingly, the estimate may not be indicative of the amounts that we could realize in a current market exchange.&amp;nbsp; The use of different market assumptions or valuation methodologies could have a material effect on the estimated fair value amounts.&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The Company&amp;#x2019;s non-qualified deferred compensation plan assets consist of money market and mutual funds invested in domestic and international marketable securities that are directly observable in active markets. &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;The fair value measurement of the earn-out contingent consideration obligation relates to the acquisitions of Sin In A Tin &lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;font-size:5pt;top:-4pt;position:relative;line-height:100%&gt;TM&lt;/font&gt;&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt; in September 2014 and Willamette Valley Fruit Company in May 2013, and is included in accrued liabilities and other long-term liabilities in the consolidated balance sheets.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The fair value measurement is based upon significant inputs not observable in the market.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Changes in the value of the obligation are recorded as income or expense in our consolidated statements of operations.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;To determine the fair value, we valued the contingent consideration liability based on the expected probability weighted earn-out payments corresponding to the performance thresholds agreed to under the applicable purchase agreements.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The expected earn-out payments were then present valued by applying a discount rate that captures a market participants view of the risk associated with the expected earn-out payments. In fiscal 2016 and 2015, we increased our estimate of the total earn-out expected to be achieved, which resulted in an increase in operating expenses of $0.3 million and&amp;nbsp; $0.3 million during the years ended December 31, 2016 and December 26, 2015, respectively.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
			&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;
		&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;p style=margin:0pt;text-indent:36pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:07.38%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size:10pt;padding-right:3.6pt;text-align:right; nowrap=nowrap&gt;&lt;div style=float:left&gt;&lt;/div&gt;247
				&lt;/td&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

						&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;tr&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:87.54%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;
					&lt;p style=margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.2pt;text-indent: -7.2pt;font-family:Times New Roman
Times
serif;font-size: 10pt;&gt;
						&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Sin In A Tin earn-out revaluation&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;
				&lt;td valign=bottom style=width:02.48%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #CCEEFF;padding:0pt;&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

						&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman

						&lt;font style=display:inline;&gt;Balance at December 31, 2016&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
				&lt;/td&gt;

					&lt;p style=margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman
